# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rest-api-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rest-api-design/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:rest-api-design/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:rest-api-design/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:rest-api-design/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:rest-api-design/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:rest-api-design/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:rest-api-design/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:rest-api-design/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:rest-api-design/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:rest-api-design/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:rest-api-design/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:rest-api-design/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:rest-api-design/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:rest-api-design/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:rest-api-design/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:rest-api-design/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:rest-api-design/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:rest-api-design/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:rest-api-design/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:rest-api-design/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:rest-api-design/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:rest-api-design/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:rest-api-design/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:rest-api-design/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:rest-api-design/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:rest-api-design/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:rest-api-design/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:rest-api-design/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:rest-api-design/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:rest-api-design/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:rest-api-design/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:rest-api-design/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:rest-api-design/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:rest-api-design/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:rest-api-design/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] With HATEOAS, a client interacts with a network application whose application servers provide information dynamically through hypermedia.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] A REST client needs little to no prior knowledge about how to interact with an application or server beyond a generic understanding of hypermedia.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] By contrast, clients and servers in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) interact through a fixed interface shared through documentation or an interface description language (IDL).
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The restrictions imposed by HATEOAS decouple client and server.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] This enables server functionality to evolve independently.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The term was coined in 2000 by Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] A user-agent makes an HTTP request to a REST API through an entry point URL.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] All subsequent requests the user-agent may make are discovered inside the response to each request.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The media types used for these representations, and the link relations they may contain, are part of the API.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The client transitions through application states by selecting from the links within a representation or by manipulating the representation in other ways afforded by its media type.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] In this way, RESTful interaction is driven by hypermedia, rather than out-of-band information.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The response contains these possible follow-up links: POST a deposit, withdrawal, transfer, or close request (to close the account).
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] As an example, later, after the account has been overdrawn, there is a different set of available links, because the account is overdrawn.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] Now only one link is available: to deposit more money (by POSTing to deposits).
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] In its current *state*, the other links are not available.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] Hence the term *Engine of Application State*.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] What actions are possible varies as the state of the resource varies.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] A client does not need to understand every media type and communication mechanism offered by the server.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The ability to understand new media types may be acquired at run-time through "code-on-demand" provided to the client by the server.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The HATEOAS constraint is an essential part of the "uniform interface" feature of REST, as defined in Roy Fielding's doctoral dissertation.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] Fielding has further described the concept on his blog.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] The purpose of some of the strictness of this and other REST constraints, Fielding explains, is "software design on the scale of decades: every detail is intended to promote software longevity and independent evolution.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] Many of the constraints are directly opposed to short-term efficiency.
[src:rest-api-design/hateoas] Unfortunately, people are fairly good at short-term design, and usually awful at long-term design".
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:rest-api-design/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:rest-api-design/rest] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The **Richardson Maturity Model** (**RMM**) is a maturity model suggested in 2008 by Leonard Richardson which classifies Web APIs based on their adherence and conformity to each of the model's four levels.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The aim of the research of the model as stated by the author was to find out the relationship between the constraints of REST and other forms of web services.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] It divides the principal parts of RESTful design into three steps: resource identification (URI), HTTP verbs, and hypermedia controls (e.g. hyperlinks).
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The RMM can be employed to determine how well a Web service architecture adheres to REST principles.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] It categorizes a Web API into four levels (from 0 to 3) with each higher level corresponding to a more complete adherence to REST design.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The next level also contains all the characteristics of the previous one.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Other classification systems for Web API services design also exist, such as CoHA and WS3.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The lowest level of the model describes a Web API with a single URI (typically POST over HTTP) accepting all the range of operations supported by the service.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Resources in this form cannot be well-defined.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Messaging is done in XML, JSON, or other text formats.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] These are typical RPC POX and many SOAP services.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Level zero systems don't classify as RESTful.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Introduces resources and allows requests for individual URIs (still all typically POST) for separate actions instead of exposing one universal endpoint (API).
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The API resources are still generalized but it is possible to identify the scope of each one.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Level One design is not RESTful, yet it is organizing the API in the direction of becoming one.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The system starts making use of HTTP Verbs.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] This allows for further specialization of the resource and thus narrows down the functionality of each individual operation within the service.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The principal separation at this level consists in splitting a given resource into two – one request for obtaining data only (GET), the other for modifying the data (POST).
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Further granularization is also possible.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] GET requests only fetch data, POST/PUT calls introduce new and update existing data, and DELETE requests remove or otherwise invalidate previous actions.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] One drawback of providing a distributed service with more than GET and POST verbs per resource might be growing complexity of using such a system.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] The last level introduces the hypermedia representation.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] Also called HATEOAS (Hypermedia As The Engine of Application State), these are elements embedded in the response messages of resources which can establish a relation between individual data entities returned from and passed to the APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] For instance, a GET request to a hotel reservation system might return a number of available rooms along with hypermedia links (these would be html hyperlink controls in the early days of the model) allowing the client to book specific rooms.
[src:rest-api-design/richardson-maturity-model] This is the last level of the Richardson Maturity Model.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:rest-api-design/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] In web development, a **webhook** is a method of augmenting or altering the behavior of a web page or web application with custom callbacks.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] These callbacks may be maintained, modified, and managed by third-party users who need not be affiliated with the originating website or application.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] In 2007, Jeff Lindsay coined the term *webhook* from the computer programming term *hook*.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] Webhooks are "user-defined HTTP callbacks".
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] They are usually triggered by some event, such as pushing code to a repository, a purchase, a comment being posted to a blog and many more use cases.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] When that event occurs, the source site makes an HTTP request to the URL configured for the webhook.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] Users can configure them to cause events on one site to invoke behavior on another.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] Common uses are to trigger builds with continuous integration systems or to notify bug tracking systems.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] Because webhooks use HTTP, they can be integrated into web services without adding new infrastructure.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] When the client (the originating website or application) makes a webhook call to the third-party user's server, the incoming POST request should be authenticated to avoid a spoofing attack and its timestamp verified to avoid a replay attack.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] The sender may choose to keep a constant list of IP addresses from which requests will be sent.
[src:rest-api-design/webhook] This is not a sufficient security measure on its own, but it is useful for when the receiving endpoint is behind a firewall or NAT.
